<item>
  <title>Kernel Methods and SVM</title>
  <dc:creator>Ray Wang</dc:creator>
  <link>https://changruiraywang.com/blog/2025-07-11-kernel-methods-and-svm/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 


<!-- source: https://github.com/gadenbuie/garrickadenbuie-com/blob/main/_partials/title-block-link-buttons/title-block.html -->
<!-- 
<header id="title-block-header" class="quarto-title-block default">
<div class="quarto-title"> 
-->
<!-- <header id="title-block-header" class="quarto-title-block default page-columns"> -->
<!-- <div class="quarto-title page-columns page-full featured-image p-4" style="background-image: url(featured.png), url(featured.jpg), url(../featured.jpg);"> -->



<section id="why-kernels" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="why-kernels">Why Kernels?</h2>
<p>Adding non-linear features is a typical approach to reducing bias when building a machine learning model. Such features include two-way, three-way or even higher interaction terms.</p>
<p>With the focus of machine learning models being prediction accuracy instead of model interpretability, one can add as many non-linear terms as possible, in the hope that the practice reveals hidden relationships among the data. However, when there are many original features, the non-linear terms can quickly become computationally expensive.</p>
<p>Consider a d-dimensional feature vector <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D">:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D%20=%20%5Cbegin%7Bpmatrix%7D%20x_1%20%5C%5C%20%5Cvdots%20%5C%5C%20x_d%20%5Cend%7Bpmatrix%7D"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_1"> through <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_d"> represent the features of an observation. For example, if <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D"> represents the feature vector of a house, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_1"> through <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_d"> could be area, year built, number of bedrooms, and other features of the house.</p>
<p>To add as many interaction terms as possible, we can have a transformation <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cphi(x)"> such that:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cphi(x)%20=%20%5Cbegin%7Bpmatrix%7D%20x_1%20%5C%5C%20%5Cvdots%20%5C%5C%20x_d%20%5C%5C%20x_1x_2%20%5C%5C%20%5Cvdots%20%5C%5C%20x_%7Bd-1%7Dx_d%20%5Cend%7Bpmatrix%7D"></p>
<p>With a feature vector of length <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?d">, a transformation <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cphi(x)"> that contains all possible interaction terms is of length <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?2%5Ed">. As a result, the dimension of the transformed features becomes high and if we calculate the higher-dimension terms one by one, the training of the model may become slow or even unfeasible.</p>
<p>So one may ask: is there an easier way to include the non-linear terms in a model in a cost-effective manner?</p>
<p>The answer is something called the <strong>kernel trick</strong>. It allows us to build models with transformed features using the original features only, without ever having to calculate the actual high-dimension features.</p>
<p>The kernel trick takes a two-step detour:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li>Find a kernel function that takes low-dimension features and returns the <strong>inner products</strong> of high-dimension features.</li>
<li>Find a machine learning model that takes the <strong>inner products</strong> of features among pairs of observations as input.</li>
</ol>
</section>
<section id="what-are-kernels" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="what-are-kernels">What are Kernels?</h2>
<p>Kernel functions take low-dimension features <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%20=%20%5Cbegin%7Bpmatrix%7D%20x_1%20%5C%5C%20%5Cvdots%20%5C%5C%20x_d%20%5Cend%7Bpmatrix%7D"> as input and return the inner product of high-dimension features.</p>
<p>Kernels often appear in the context of similarity, since the similarity of two observations is usually calculated as the inner product of their feature vectors.</p>
<p>As a toy example, consider two observations with feature vectors <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(180,%2070)"> and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(160,%2050)">.</p>
<p>To calculate their similarity, we take the inner product:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Clangle%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D%20%5Crangle%20=%20180%20%5Ctimes%20160%20+%2070%20%5Ctimes%2050"></p>
<p>Now suppose we wish to better represent the similarity by adding a non-linear transformation:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cphi(%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D)%20=%20(x_1%5E2,%5C%20x_2%5E2,%5C%20%5Csqrt%7B2%7D%5C,x_1%20x_2)"></p>
<p>The inner product of two transformed vectors becomes:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Clangle%20%5Cphi(%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D),%20%5Cphi(%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20%5Crangle%20=%20180%5E2%20%5Ccdot%20160%5E2%20+%2070%5E2%20%5Ccdot%2050%5E2%20+%20%5Csqrt%7B2%7D%20%5Ccdot%20180%20%5Ccdot%2070%20%5Ccdot%20%5Csqrt%7B2%7D%20%5Ccdot%20160%20%5Ccdot%2050%20=%201%7B,%7D043%7B,%7D290%7B,%7D000"></p>
<p>This requires computing <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Csqrt%7B2%7D%5C,x_1%20x_2"> first — 11 multiplications and 2 summations in total.</p>
<p>However, using the kernel function <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?K(%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20=%20(%5Clangle%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D%20%5Crangle)%5E2">:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?K(%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20=%20(x_1%20z_1%20+%20x_2%20z_2)%5E2%20=%20(180%20%5Ctimes%20160%20+%2070%20%5Ctimes%2050)%5E2%20=%201%7B,%7D043%7B,%7D290%7B,%7D000"></p>
<p>Only 3 multiplications and 1 summation — same result, far less computation. This demonstrates that kernel functions give us the inner product of high-dimensional features without ever computing those features directly.</p>
<section id="polynomial-kernel" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="polynomial-kernel">Polynomial Kernel</h3>
<p>Suppose observation <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x"> has two variables <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_1"> and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_2">:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%20=%20%5Cbegin%7Bpmatrix%7D%20x_1%20%5C%5C%20x_2%20%5Cend%7Bpmatrix%7D"></p>
<p>We want to add a bias term plus the square and interaction terms:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cphi(x)%20=%20%5Cbegin%7Bpmatrix%7D%201%20%5C%5C%20x_1%20%5C%5C%20x_2%20%5C%5C%20x_1%20x_2%20%5C%5C%20x_1%5E2%20%5C%5C%20x_2%5E2%20%5Cend%7Bpmatrix%7D"></p>
<p>The inner product of two transformed observations is:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Clangle%20%5Cphi(%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D),%20%5Cphi(%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20%5Crangle%20=%201%20+%20x_1%20z_1%20+%20x_2%20z_2%20+%20x_1%20x_2%20z_1%20z_2%20+%20x_1%5E2%20z_1%5E2%20+%20x_2%5E2%20z_2%5E2"></p>
<p>This is equivalent to the 2nd degree polynomial kernel:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?K_%7B%5Ctext%7Bpoly%7D(2)%7D(%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20=%20(1%20+%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D%5ET%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%5E2"></p>
<p>To verify, expand the squared term:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(1%20+%20x_1%20z_1%20+%20x_2%20z_2)%5E2%20=%201%20+%20x_1%20z_1%20+%20x_2%20z_2%20+%20x_1%20x_2%20z_1%20z_2%20+%20x_1%5E2%20z_1%5E2%20+%20x_2%5E2%20z_2%5E2"></p>
<p>In general, the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">-degree polynomial kernel is defined as:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?K_%7B%5Ctext%7Bpoly%7D(n)%7D(%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20=%20(1%20+%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D%5ET%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%5En"></p>
<p>Polynomial kernels are building blocks of the most powerful kernel — the radial basis function kernel.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-radial-basis-function-rbf-kernel" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-radial-basis-function-rbf-kernel">The Radial Basis Function (RBF) Kernel</h3>
<p>The RBF kernel is defined as:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?K_%7B%5Ctext%7BRBF%7D%7D(x,%20z)%20=%20e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Csigma%5E2%7D%20%5C%7Cx%20-%20z%5C%7C%5E2%7D"></p>
<p>It takes the idea of adding interaction terms to the extreme by considering an <strong>infinite</strong> number of interactions. To see why, expand the exponent:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Csigma%5E2%7D(x-z)%5ET(x-z)%7D%20=%20e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Csigma%5E2%7D(x%5ET%20x%20-%202x%5ET%20z%20+%20z%5ET%20z)%7D%20=%20e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Csigma%5E2%7D(x%5ET%20x%20+%20z%5ET%20z)%7D%20%5Ccdot%20e%5E%7Bx%5ET%20z%7D"></p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?=%20e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%5Csigma%5E2%7D(x%5ET%20x%20+%20z%5ET%20z)%7D%20%5Ccdot%20e%5E%7Bx%5ET%20z%20+%201%7D%20%5Ccdot%20e%5E%7B-1%7D"></p>
<p>Gathering all terms except <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?e%5E%7Bx%5ET%20z%20+%201%7D"> into a constant <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?C">:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?=%20C%20%5Ccdot%20e%5E%7Bx%5ET%20z%20+%201%7D"></p>
<p>By definition, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?e%5Ex%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bn=0%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cdfrac%7Bx%5En%7D%7Bn!%7D">, so:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?e%5E%7Bx%5ET%20z%20+%201%7D%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bn=0%7D%5E%7B%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B(1%20+%20x%5ET%20z)%5En%7D%7Bn!%7D"></p>
<p>Notice that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(1%20+%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D%5ET%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%5En"> is exactly the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">-degree polynomial kernel <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?K_%7B%5Ctext%7Bpoly%7D(n)%7D">. Therefore, the RBF kernel is an <strong>infinite sum of polynomial kernels</strong> from degree 1 to <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cinfty">.</p>
</section>
</section>
<section id="kernelized-algorithms" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="kernelized-algorithms">Kernelized Algorithms</h2>
<p>Kernel functions efficiently capture high-dimensional information using low-dimensional data. But how do they connect to building a machine learning model?</p>
<p>It turns out that many models can be re-expressed so that they depend only on the <strong>inner products</strong> of feature vectors between pairs of observations. Two key examples are Linear Regression and Support Vector Machines.</p>
<section id="kernelized-linear-regression" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="kernelized-linear-regression">Kernelized Linear Regression</h3>
<p>The conventional linear regression model can be re-expressed as a linear combination of inner products of input feature vectors.</p>
<p>Denote the regression parameter vector as <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D">. The loss function is:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cell(%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D)%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20(%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D%5ET%20x_i%20-%20y_i)%5E2"></p>
<p>Gradient descent updates <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D"> as:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?w_%7Bt+1%7D%20=%20w_t%20-%20s%20%5Cleft(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20%5Cell%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D%7D%5Cright)"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?s"> is the learning rate. The gradient can be expressed as a linear combination of input feature vectors:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%20%5Cell%7D%7B%5Cpartial%20%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D%7D%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Cunderbrace%7B2(%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D%5ET%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D_i%20-%20y_i)%7D_%7B%5Cgamma_i%7D%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D_i%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Cgamma_i%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D_i"></p>
<p>By induction, if we express <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D"> as a linear combination of all input vectors:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_i%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D_i"></p>
<p>then gradient descent preserves this structure at every step:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D_1%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_i%5E0%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D_i%20-%20s%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Cgamma_i%5E0%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D_i%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20(%5Calpha_i%5E0%20-%20s%5Cgamma_i%5E0)%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D_i%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_i%5E1%20%5Cmathbf%7Bx%7D_i"></p>
<p>This means the prediction for the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?j">th observation can be written entirely in terms of inner products:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?h(x_j)%20=%20%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D%5ET%20x_j%20+%20b%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_i%20x_i%5ET%20x_j%20+%20b"></p>
<p>And for a new observation <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D">:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?h(%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20=%20%5Cmathbf%7Bw%7D%5ET%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D%20+%20b%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_i%20x_i%5ET%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D%20+%20b"></p>
<p>The prediction is a weighted sum of inner products between <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D"> and each training point <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_i">.</p>
</section>
<section id="support-vector-machine" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="support-vector-machine">Support Vector Machine</h3>
<p><strong>Primal problem:</strong></p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmin_%7Bw,%5C,%20w_0%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D%20w%5ET%20w%20%5Cquad%20%5Ctext%7Bs.t.%7D%20%5Cquad%20%5Cforall%20i:%20%5C%20y_i(w%5ET%20x_i%20+%20w_0)%20%5Cgeq%201"></p>
<p><strong>Dual problem:</strong></p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmin_%7B%5Calpha%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Csum_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20y_i%20y_j%20%5Calpha_i%20%5Calpha_j%20x_i%5ET%20x_j%20-%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_i"></p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Ctext%7Bs.t.%7D%20%5Cquad%200%20%5Cleq%20%5Calpha_i%20%5Cleq%20C,%20%5Cquad%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_i%20y_i%20=%200"></p>
<p>The optimization depends only on the inner products <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_i%5ET%20x_j"> between pairs of observations. Solving for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?w">:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?w%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_i%20y_i%20x_i"></p>
<p>The decision rule for a new observation <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D"> is:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?h(%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20=%20%5Ctext%7Bsign%7D%5C!%5Cleft(%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20%5Calpha_i%20y_i%5C,%20k(x_i,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20+%20b%5Cright)"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?b"> is solved using <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?w">.</p>
<section id="svm-as-a-smart-nearest-neighbor" class="level4">
<h4 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="svm-as-a-smart-nearest-neighbor">SVM as a Smart Nearest Neighbor</h4>
<p>The k-nearest neighbor algorithm classifies as:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?h(%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20=%20%5Ctext%7Bsign%7D%5C!%5Cleft(%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bn%7D%20y_i%5C,%20%5Cdelta%5E%7Bnn%7D(x_i,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%5Cright)"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cdelta%5E%7Bnn%7D(x_i,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)%20=%201"> if <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_i"> is among the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k"> nearest neighbors of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D">, and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?0"> otherwise.</p>
<p>SVM can be seen as a smarter version of KNN with three additional components: <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k(x_i,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D),%5C%20%5Calpha_i,%5C%20b">.</p>
<ul>
<li><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?k(x_i,%20%5Cmathbf%7Bz%7D)"> acts as a <strong>distance-based weight</strong> — with the RBF kernel, the test point places a Gaussian around itself and weighs nearby points more heavily.</li>
<li><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Calpha_i"> <strong>removes redundant training points</strong> that are already classified correctly (support vectors are the only ones with <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Calpha_i%20%3E%200">).</li>
<li><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?b"> is the <strong>bias term</strong>.</li>
</ul>
</section>
